									<p>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
										Viewed 236 times<br>
									</span>

									
									</td>

						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#330000" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												But we're not talking about reaggroing.  We're talking about a situation where the documentation says it should be possible to lose aggro, but it is not.<br><br>You said you believe constructs follow "special rules."  If so, those rules predate Fading Memories by quite some time.  My guess is that someone neglected to consider the interaction of escape-type skills with certain pre-existing "special rules" MOBs, resulting in unexpected behavior, such as FM failing for no obvious or predictable reason.<br><br>It's the unexpected and unpredictable behavior part that I'm having problems with.  Trying to play it off as a legitimate game challenge would be a cop-out.  Lack of capricious punishment is a central principle in game design.  If something is going to go wrong, you should be at least in principle able to foresee and understand the screw-up.<br><br>For instance, fading in front of an aggro, see-invis MOB is a mistake you make at most one time without foreseeing the resulting problem.  That's a failure you can understand, predict, and try to avoid.  MOBs that inexplicably ignore the skill completely are not.  That would include any secondary "memory" mechanisms that might cause the MOB to "remember" you for zone-wide reaggroing purposes outside of the normal MOB aggro rules (if such a thing actually exists).<br><br>If such a thing <i>does</i> exist, then in a way that's an even bigger problem, because consistency of the behavior depends upon the player knowing something about the internal mechanisms of the game.  I tend to think effective playing in EQ necessitates too much awareness of the hate list in particular as it is.<br><br>"This skill does X except when, for secret reasons known only to us, it doesn't" is not a good way for anything to behave.
																		
										</td></tr>
