						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#330000" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												Kute, you're being unnecessarily confrontational about this.  The fact I don't agree with you is not evidence I haven't been reading.  It's possible for me to simply disagree.<br><br>Your example about Selo's is spurious.  If you're using Selo's and a MOB is faster than you, then it's pretty obvious what happened.  The MOB was faster than you.  Your example about charming has similar problems.  You know what happened when your pet starts beating the crud out of you.  You're expecting it, in fact.  And you <i>do</i> get a "spell wore off" message when your charm breaks.<br><br>In fact, I agree that the constructs may be instantly re-aggroing instead of never dropping aggro, but the effect is the same, and there's still a problem with the behavior of the encounter.<br><br>This is a situation where, given a normal understanding of game mechanics, something happens that is not expected and not explained.  We all know roughly what sorts of things get you aggro.  Even under the re-aggro scenario this is a case where none of the usual aggro triggers obtain, and yet you get onto the hate list anyway, and it happens in a way that silently breaks the hate management techniques players are accustomed to using.<br><br>As I said before, it's not unreasonable to expect some sort of indication that this is happening.  Making a challenging game involves creating encounters that require players to use their abilities in creative ways.  Unexpectedly, capriciously and silently disabling players' abilities is not challenging.  It's just frustrating.<br><br>Incidentally, if these mobs behave the way you describe, then it's a bad behavior to include in any MOB.  If a MOB can aggro anyone in the zone without regard to distance or LOS, it encourages griefing.  Someone could spawn and aggro all the constructs they could find and gate out.  Imagine if someone did that while you were trying to knock out one of the DN raids for your epic, for example.  They would be able to throw completely anonymous trains at you without even risking going near your camp.
																		
										</td></tr>
